{"/service/ndnp/wa/batch_wa_american_ver02/data/sn88085620/00211107625/1921021801/0591.xml":{"full_text":"Page Four\nBACHELDER CORNEIL\nBETTER CLOTHES\u2014UNION MADE\n1617-19 HEWITT AVENUE\nEverett, Wash.\nMAKE THIS YOUR MAIL ORDER HOUSE\u2014\nBefore Buying Your New Spring Garments\nBe Sure to See the Latest\nModels in\nMODART CORSETS\n\u2014\"First the corset\u2014then gown' is always the rule of the\nwoman who makes a study of fashionable apparel.\n\u2014The new Spring Modart models still further reveal the\nfact that this corset is without an equal as a figure shap\ning garment. It is beautifully designed to mold the\nfigure into lines of symetry and will maintain these lines\nwhen once developed.\n\u2014All MODART Corsets lace in front because front adjust\nment means right adjustment. The absence of laces in the\nback gives better form and wonderful smoothness in gown\nfitting.\n\u2014You will be assured of being properly corseted if you\nselect your new MODART in our corset section. When you\nhave selected the corset MODART model and have been\nfitted by our expert corsetierre, you will feel so much\nbetter and look so much better that you will seem to have\nbecome a new woman.\nUNFAIR LIST\nHAKBKK SHOPS\nI. H. Turner, 1104 Hewitt; Barnhart Shop.\nMonroe.\nBUILDING LABORERS\nL. Starke, Emit Mltersbach, John Grant.\nCOFFEE AND TEA HOUSES\nManning* C'oWee House on Hewitt between\nColby and Wetmore.\nCONOBNBED MILK\nLibby. McNeil Libby, Packers and Can\nn\u00abrs; Carnation, Aster, Mt. Vernon and\nWaehlnfltton brand- Yakima City Creamery.\nCONTRACTORS\nChrist Kruppler Sons and the Standard\nOil Bids., at corner of Pacific and Virginia.\nELECTRICIANS\nF. R. Hare, electrical contractor John\nThueson.\nIISH CCJMPAMKS\nSan Juan Fish Co., Seattle.\nGENERAL MKRt'H ANDISE\nliut.ers, The Star. Bon Marche of Seattle.\nMEAT MAKhKIS\nThe Municipal Meat Market and it.s Prop\nrietor, A. C. Snider; ShineiS* Market, IM': 1\nHewitt.\nMunicipal Meat Market, A. M. Farley, Manaiier.\nPLASTERERS\nA. C. Wright, A. L. Knapp. Booth, W. L.\nPorter.\nPLUMBERS\nOtto Mir.', John Theuson, Mr. P lam back\nSHIPYARD\nThe Norway-Pacific.\nMISCELLANEOUS\nC. W. Anguish, 35U5 Lombard; American\nPec kins Co.. Everett; Cat. Smilley and Sonc\nYvitz Gerald; M. Anderson and house, 21ot* l .j\niiainier Avenue; R. J. McCain, lumber deal\ner; Mr. Burden and his house, iiSll Maple\n'.reet; Everett Eruit Products Co. ;K. S.\nI.ang Manufacturing Co. of Seattle.\nROSIER OF UNIONS\nUnder this head will be printed weekly the\n*.ames of unions, dates and places of meet\ning, name* <_\u2022\u00a3 presidents and secretaries, or\nbusiness agents, with their bouse or phone\nnumbers, at soc per month. The advantage\nof this Roster will be readily seen. Corrections\n::iade as soon as possible afo-r notification.\nAMERICAN FEDERATION OF\nLABOR\nAddress Samuel Gompers, President; or\n1 rank Morrison, Secretary, A. F. of L. Bids.\nWashington, D. C.\nWASHINGTON STATE FEDERATION\nOF LABOR\nWilliam M. Short, President, 508-9 Maynard\nBldg Seattle. Wash.\n1- W. Buck, Secretary-Treasurer, 508-9 May\nnaru Bide., Seattle. Wash.\n(ENTRAL LABOR COUNCIL\nMeets \u2022very Wednesday night ut m o*eloek,\nin Hall 1, Labor Tempi*. J. H. Michel,\nPresident ;O. F. W efferling. Secretary.\nLOCAL UNIONS\nBarken Local No. lit, \u2014Meets 2nd Thursday\nin eacn month. Ike Mac Donald. President.\n2828 KocKefeller avenue; W. C. Davis, Sec\nretary-Treasurer, I\u00bb513 Hewitt avenue.\nlioilermakern' Unien, Everett No. sno\u2014 Meet*\nthe 2nd und 4th Wednesday nights of each\nmonth, at the Labor Temple Wm. Myers,\nPresident, 191il Virginia St., Everett:\nGrant Wirick, Corresponding -Secretary.\nPinehurst. All brothers invited to attend.\nElectrical Workers, No. ltd, meets in Hall\nNo. 1, I.abor Temple, on Monday at 8 p.m.\nPresident. J. E. Pentorf, Labor Temple.\nSec.. J. M. Gibba. 3119 Oakea, Phone White\n367.\nEngineers, Local No. 719, meeta every Thurs\nday in Hall 5. Labor Temple. A. H. Herbst,\nPresident, 1717 Colby. Phone Red 313.'\nHurry C. Parks, Secretary, 3018 Nerton.\nPhone Black a 62.\nLongshoremen No. 3\u00bb-s, meets Monday nights\nat 7:BU, at 2839 Bond Street. President,\nFrank Preston. 2989 Uond Secretary, G.\nD. Bryan. 2939 Bond; Business Agent, E\nJannsen, 2939 Bond. Phone 705.\nPainters, No. 339, meeta every Tuesday at 8\np. m. President, A. C. HaUoe. 171\u00bb lTth\nSt., Phone White I*6l. H. Arends. Secre\ntary. 2426 Virginia, Phone Blue \"35.\nRetail Clerks, Local No. 448 Meets first\nThursday of each month in hall No. 3, in\nthe Labor Temple. A. J. Hennessey, Presi\ndent; R R. KwaiweU. Ut Vice-President.\nE. J. Edney. 2nd Vice President; L T\nJohnson. Sec.-Treas. F. J. Scuilto, Rec. Sec.\nStage Employees and Moving Picture Oper\nators Arthur A Petteraen. President.\nI*o\u00df Wetmore; Fred Tucker. Recording\nSecretary. 34)01 Everett; Geo. Fauver\nFin. Sec.-Treas.. 2r.i>7 Wetmore.\nTeamsters Local No. 99\u2014Meets in Hell 2\nI.abor Temple, every Tuesday evening.\nT. S. Overvold, Secretary, 262\", Wetmore\nN. R. Thompson, President; 130! Wall.\nTinker* orkers. Local No. Meets Ist and\n3rd Friday, and 2nd and 4th Sundays in\nLabor Temple, at 7 p. m. .1. C. Rath. Prest..\n2U17'., Hewitt Phone Mam 997R, Thomas\nHolmstn.ro, Kec. Bee., ISIO Lombard; M. A.\nMeyer. Fin. Sec., 2227 Summit.\nSmoke BLUE RIBBON' Ut Cigar.\nThe union la!>el i- a \"home indus\ntry\" builder and should receive your\n(\u2022atronage.\nSummer Prices\nReached in\nMILK\nlie Per Quart\nMilk brought into our\nplant in the morning\nreaches the homes with\nin an hour and a half.\nPioneer-Alpine Dairy\n26th and Broadway\nMAIN 271\nOWL PHARMACY\n1607 HEWITT\nEx 17\u00ab\nSUMMONS\nIn the Superior Court of the State of\nWashington, for Snohomish County.\nUegina Colistro. plaintiff, vs. Carmel Colis\ntro, defendant.\nThe Suite of Washington, to the said\nCarmel Colistro. defendant.\nYou are hereby summoned to appear with\nin sixty (6oi days after the date of the\nfirst publication of this summons, to-wit:\nWithin sixty 1601 days after the 21st day ol\nJanuary, 1921, and defend the above en\ntitled action in the above entitled court,\nand answer the complaint of the plaintiff,\nand serve a copy of your answer upon the\nundersigned attorneys for plaintiff, at their\noffice below stated; and in case of your\nfailure so to do, judgment will he rendered\nagainst you according to the demand of the\ncomplaint, which has been filed with the\nclerk of said court.\nThe object of this action is to obtain a\ndivorce from the defendant on the grounds\nof cruelty and non-support.\nE. C. DAILEY,\nA. E. DAILEY,\nAttorneys for Plaintiff.\nOffice and P. O. address-Stokes Build\ning. Everett, Snohomish County, Wash\nington.\nFirst Publication Jan. 21, 1921.\nLast Publication March 4, 1921.\nForgot Promises\nJust Like \"We\" Did\nLondon, England, Feb. 12.\u2014The\npresent unemployed problem again\nreminds trade unionists of the his\ntoric conference of employers and\nemployes, held two years ago in\nthis city. The meeting was address\ned by Premier Lloyd George and\nthe people of Great Britain and the\nworld were notified that at last an\nunderstanding between \"capital\n(capitalists) and labor\" was in\nsight. Lloyd George stated, that\nwhatever was agreed upon he would\nat once give the force of law.\nTh'; conference agreed on maxi\nmum hours, minimum wages, meth\nod of preventing unemployment, or,\nalternatively, providing adequate\nmaintenance while unemployed or\npartially employed. A joint indus\ntrial parliament was also agreed to.\nThis was intended to settle differ\nences between employer and em\nployed before they reached the acute\nstage.\nThe government has forgotten,\nj the public has forgotten and unem\nj ployment is most acute with the\ngovernment suggesting that those\nemployed divide their time with\nthose not employed. A few months\nago the government was demanding\ngreater production, and thundering\n[tin the evils of idleness.\nDuring the war, American labor\nas promised industrial democracy.\nThe Government and the public\nforgot the promises, but labor\ndidn't.\nSmoke OLYMPIC CLUB 10c cigar.\nR. R. WAGE CUT\nTURNED DOWN\nChicago, 111., Feb. 10.\u2014Declaring\nthat they were \"holding the pass\"\nagainst a concreted assault upon the\nwage rights of two millions of their\nt< How railroad workers, the two\nthousand employees of the Atlanta,\nBirmingham Atlantic Railroad to-\nI day presented their ease before the\nUnited States Railroad Labor Board.\nThe employees of this small, obscure\nsouthern road were the shock ab\nsorbers, it was stated, in the im\npending gigantic clash between the\nmanagements of the country's rail\nroads as a whole and the workers,\nand the wage reduction asked by\nthis road was denounced as a smoke\nscreen behind which railroad and\nfinancial interests sought to con\nceal their attack on railroad labor\norganizations in an open shop cam\npaign which was nothing more nor\nless than an anti-union campaign.\nNeither increased wages nor the\npresent business depression was re\nsponsible for the inability of the\nAtlanta, Birmingham Atlantic to\npay the wage rates fixed by the\nRailroad Labor Board last July, it\nwas declared, but the financial con\ndition of the road was brought\nabout by years of gross mismanage*\nment and inefficiency, nnd there\nhas been no reduction in living costs\nto justify any reduction whatever\nin wages.\n\\V. S- Carter, president of the\nBrotherhood of Locomomtive Fire\nmen and E. P, Curtis, for the Broth\nerhood of Railroad Trainmen, pre\nsented the case for the employees.\nNumerous exhibits prepared under\nthe supervision of W. Jett Lauck,\nof Washington, consulting economist\nfor the railroad labor organization,\nwere laid before the Board. Mr.\nLauck testified as to the data on\nfinances, L. S. Trigg, of Washing\nton, presented the exhibits on pro\nductive efficiency and labor costs,\nand Arthur Sturgis, of Boston, was\nthe expert called on the cost of\nliving.\n\"As a final point in this contro\nversy,\" said Mr. Carter, in his state\nment to the Board, \"it should be\nborne in mind that even if the\nwages of employees of the Atlanta,\nBirmingham Atlantic should be\nreduced as proposed, the ultimate\nfinancial condition of the property\nwill not be improved. It is ad\nmitted by the President, Mr. Pugg,\nthat the wage reduction which he\nseeks will simply enable the road to\ncany on operations in the hope that\nwith a revival of business prosperity\nconditions will so improve that the\nrailroad may eventually retire some\nof its outstanding obligations. The\npresent condition of the finances of\nthe road has been brought about\nthrough years of inefficiency and\nmismanagement, and it is presump\ntious to ask the employees to suf\nfer a wage reduction, not justified\nby reduced living costs or changes\nin other conditions upon which the\nrates were based, in order that the\nmanagement may ultimately retire\nbonds issued during the days of the\ncompany's financial profligacy.\n\"It is unthinkable that the em\nployees should be made to suffer be\ncause of the obvious financial jug\ngling and mismanagement, which is\nproved conclusively by the data pre\nsented to this Board.\n\"The real causes of the present\ndeplorable financial condition of the\nroad are not to be found in the in\ncreased wages of the employees,\nnor even in the present temporary\nbusiness depression, which, it is\nclaimed, has curtailed the road's\nearning power in spite of increased\nrates. The insolvency of the At\nlanta, Birmingham Atlantic is an\ninheritance from the days when the\nbuilding and the equipping of the\nroad were financially manipulated\nbetween favored individuals and fa\nvored corporations, such as the At\nlantic Birmingham Construction\nCompany; it is an inheritance from\nthe days of mismanagement by\n'friendly' receivers; it is the mere\ncontinuation of a financial condition\nthat has existed since the inception\nof the road. To force upon the\nworkers the burden of maintaining\nthis bankrupt property's worthless\nsecurities; to reduce the wages of\nthe employees merely for the pur\npose of giving the Old Colony Trust\nCompany, of Boston, another oppor\ntunity to 'reorganize' the road along\nthe same lines as prevailed during\nthe questionable receivership of\n1909, would mean the infliction of\na hardship and injustice too great\nto bear-\"\nThe United States Railroad Labor\nBoaid refused to reduce the wages\nof the employees.\nTo Make Work for\nThe Unemployed\nHundreds of millions of dollars\nhave been appropriated or raised by\nbond issues the past three years to\nbe used for road building and road\nimprovements. Comparatively little\nof the money has been spent. The\nshortage of labor and material has\nbeen the reason assigned for the\ndelay in getting under way more\nextensively.\nBut now the kind of labor mostly\nemployed to produce road building\nmaterials\u2014stone, lime, cement, sand,\ngravel, asphalt, tar, etc. is far\nfrom being fully employed. Men in\nthese lines seek employment. And\nit would be for the public interest,\nas well as to their own individual\ninterest, if these men were work\ning and earning. Their earnings\nand expenditures would swell the\nturnover in many lines of trade;\noperatives producing the goods sold\nto them would escape lay-off or\nshort time employment.\nProbably labor leaders and work\ningmen generally could do a great\ndeal to get the country's road\nbuilding program promptly under\nway on a large scale. Highway\ncommissioners and other public of\nficials controlling such work should\nbe >.een and convinced that labor is\nnow plentiful with which to go\nahead. And if properly approach\ned, merchants, ministers and public\nspirited men in all communities\nwould assist the labor bodies to get\nthe movement under way. The\nnewspapers would willignly help.\nLet's all pull together to make\nwork for the unemployed at this\ntime when employment is most\nUrgently needed.\u2014lndustrial News\nService.\nCulinary workers in Illinois are\ndemanding the passage of a one\nday-rest-in-seven law-\nTHE LABOR JOURNAL\nOld High Tariff\nAdvocates Do Not\nWant It Any More\nBecause big business has visions\nof world markets it is abanding the\ntheory that a Chinese wall, in the\nform of high tariff, must protect\nthis country from foreign competi\ntion, according to the Philadelphia\nNorth American.\nFormer high tariff advocates\nknow that if commodities of other\nnations are bailed, those nations\nwill retaliate und the prospect of\nworld markets is destroyed. It is\neven whispered that the steel trust\nhas come to the conclusion that it\ncan compete against the world and\nthat the pauper labor bugaboo has\nlost its force as this labor can be\nimported as needed, while the coun\ntries that supply the pauper labor\ncan be made a customer of Ameri\ncan steel if no barrier is placed\nagainst its products.\nThis city is the home of men who\nhave advocated the highest tariff\nbarriers possible, but the change\nfrom national capitalism to inter\nnational capitalism by these and\nother business men is indicated in\na long editorial in the North Amer\nican which says, in part:\n\"Among the advocates of a mod*\nernized tariff they will find some\npowerful interests and industrial\ncombinations prosperity was\nbuilt up under hich protection, but\nwhoso production has outgrown the\nhome market and whose future is\ndependent upon the development ol\nforeign trade.\n\"They will find in the ranks of\nthe moderate protectionists great\nbanking interests, which in the past\ncontributed heavily to campaign\nfunds on the high tariff issue, b.it\nwhose horizon has been widened and\nwhose field of operations has been\nvastly extended in recent years.\nProminent among these will be in\nternational banking houses which\nhave sold hundreds of millions of\ndollars' worth of European govern\nment loans, redeemable only through\nthe expansion of commercial rela\ntionships and the exchange of goods\nfostered by a lower tariff.\"\nChurch Unmasks\nThe \"Open\" Shop\nNew York, Feb. 11.\u2014The Social\nService Bulletin, issued by the Meth\nodist Federation for social service,\nis the latest to bombard the al\nleged \"open\" shop. This attack is\none of the many being launched\nagainst the anti-union movement by\nchurch men of all creeds.\n\"The real issue.\" says the Social\nService Bulletin, \"is the method of\nnegotiating with employes. It is a\nquestion of collective bargaining, as\nagainst individual bargaining. The\n\u25a0personal liberty' and 'freedom of\ncontract' for which the employing\ngroup stands, leaves entire control\nof hiring and firing, management,\namount and quality of product, sys\ntem of pay in the hands of the em\nployer. An individual, even though\na 'union man,' is powerless to bar\ngain over these matters.\n\"That this is the real issue of the\ncampaign is evident in the repeated\nassurance of employing groups that\nthey will not discriminate against\nunion men as such, but that they\nwill deal with them only as individ\nuals.\n\"Experience of the steel corpora\ntion in maintaining the 'open shop'\npolicy indicates that this policy is\nnot enforced without an army of\nspies. Such spy systems established\nby this and other corporations\nbreed distrust, suspicion and dis\nruption in community life.\n\"In West Virginia at the present\ntime, the determination of coal op\nerators to maintain 'open shop' con\nditions is leading to a situation\nwhich threatens civil strife in that\narea.\n\"In Alabama, military rule has\nsupplanted civil administration be\ncause coal operators are determined\nto keep out the union.\n\"Is the public ready to substitute\nfpr the collective bargaining of la\nbor the closed shop of industrial\nautocracy with its social conse\nquences? Is it willing to have these\nsocial results extended?\"\nInvestigation\nof Sawdust Ring\nThe Calder Senate committee,\nwhich was appointed 10 months ago\nto investigate the high cost of\nbuilding operations, and which\nswitched its inquiry to the high cost\nof coal, spurred on by the recent\nreports from the Federal Trade\nCommission relating to the high\ncost of lumber, has begun to look\ninto the cost of lumber as it affects\nbuilding operations.\nBut there has been other inquiries\ninto the cost of lumber made by\nSenator Kenyon of lowa. He in\ntimates that $250,000 a year is the\nminimum cost of the lumber lobby.\nHe will bring before the committee\na mass of correspondence seized\nfrom the files of the combine by\nagents of the federal trade commis\nsion. This data will show the con\nnection between the fabulous prices\npaid by the government, early in the\nwar, for lumber for the army can\ntonments, and the presence of the\nspokesmen of the combine in gov\nernment office! in Washington. It\nwill also show how the lumber bar\nons, like the big Chicago meat pack\ners, kept in close touch with events\nin the capital through a system of\nsecret spies and camouflaged news\npaper men; how the timber barons\ndodged taxation and raised their\nprices while stubbornly reducing\nproduction at a time when the\ncountry was being exhorted by these\nvery gentlemen to \"increase produc\ntion\" of goods needed for war pur\nposes.\nAs the time is short until the\nSession dies, the investigation can\nnot be completed. It will, however,\nopen many avenues for inquiry by\na new committee to be chosen next\nmonth. From lumber it may turn\nto .steel and then perhaps to oil and\nwaterpower lobbies, which are close\nly interwoven in the furtive under\nworld of Icislagtion.\nWatch for the lumber lobby ex\nposure and remember that a big\nplay for \"purifying\" the atmosphere\nof national legislation is timed to\nfollow closely upon Harding's in\nauguration.\nSuperior Court Judge Van Nos\ntrand, of San Francisco, has ruled\nthat a landlord cannot evict a ten\nant who refuses to pay more rent\nthan his lease calls for.\nTHE BATTLE OF\nTHE BIG SHIPS\n\"Whut is the use of a battleship.\nShe must be of some use, or the\nUnited States and Japan would not\nbf< building battleships.\" This ques\ntion of Sir Percy Scott, one of Eng\nland's leading naval authorities, has\njust been flatly answered by Brig.\nGen. William Mitchell, assistant\n<hief of the air service of the\nUnited States army. He declares\nthat despite naval prejudice to the\ncontrary, the armored ship is now\n\"just as helpless as the armored\nknight was when the firearm was\nbrought against him.\" General\nMitchell may be no naval expert, as\nthe navy men retort, but he does\nknow something about flying. The\ndevelopment of the torpedo and the\naeroplane, especially with the new\npossibilities of radio control, has\nmade open-minded experts wonder\nwhat is to become of the surface\nship.\nAs a result of spirited discussion\nduring recent months, the British\nhave suspended all building of cap\nital ships until the admiralty can\nreport on the whole question. Our\nown navy, however, goes blissfully\nforward building 17 battleships and\ncruisers, to cost well up toward\nthree quarters of a billion dollars.\nNo living soul knows whether they\nwill really be of any use when they\nluc done, but our admirals inssit\nthat we press on with the program.\nTo. meet this situation Senator\nBorah last week got unanimous con\nsent to a resolution asking the Sen\nate committee on naval affairs to\nreport whether it be wise to sus\npend the building program for six\nmonths in order to decide \"what\nconstitutes a modern fighting navy.\"\nCongressman Murphy of Ohio has\nintroduced a similar resolution in\nthe house. This proposal is met\nwith loud charges that it is Brit\nish propaganda to halt our naval\nadvance. As a matter of fact, it is\nplain business commonsense, and\nonly the big-navy men, the arma\nment makers, and the ultra-conserv\native naval board have reasons to\nse it. Their combined opposi\ntion, however, is formidable.\nIndirectly, the controversy con\nnects itself with the. disarmament\nfight, which rages under cover.\nSenator Borah's resolution for a\nnaval holiday is being fought with\nthe expected tactics of delay and\nunderground opposition. If the meas\nure could be brought to a vote, it\nwould pass without question. Faced\nby the possibility of indefinite delay,\nthe Idaho Senator makes a flank at\ntack, designed to secure action of\nsome kind.\nThe real situation in Washington\nis becoming increasingly clear. A\npowerful combination of business\nand naval interests is determined to\ncreate an incomparable navy. What\never stands in the way is to be\nblushed aside. The Army and Navy\nJournal frankly points out the ideas\nof this group: Throw overboard\nthe notion of \"a navy for defense\npure and simple\" and remember\nthat an adequate navy is only \"that\nnavy which can cope with any situa\ntion successfully and be ready to\nwin decisively a battle 7,000 miles\nfrom a Pacific coast base.\" It is\nuseless to argue with such a group\nthe uses of a battleship. The sole\nquestion is, have they the votes\nIf so, we shall have more battle\nships, unless the groaning taxpayer\nspeaks in far louder tones than\nhave yet been heard here.\n\"Big Biz\" Is Warned\nPhiladelphia, Feb. 12.\u2014\"Are We\nFacing Industrial War?\" asks the\nCatholic Standard and Times in a\nleading editorial on the anti-trade\nunion campaign of employers in this\ncountry.\n\"This drive,\" says the editor, \"is\nconsidered by the unions, and that\nnot without very good reason, as\nan attack upon unionism, and as a\ndeliberate attempt to undermine the\norganized labor movement. It is re\ngarded by them as a challenge and\na declaration of war. Naturally,\nthis will arouse resentment among\nthe laborers, for they are well aware\nthat most of the advantages they\nat present enjoy are due to the\nconcerted efforts of the unions. The\nunions are dear to them and they\nhave pinned their faith to them.\n\"In this attempt the employers\nmay overreach themselves and con\njure up ghosts that it will be diffi\ncult to lay. It is certain that labor\nis not in the mood to tolerate coer\ncion and to give up the standing it\nhas achieved.\n\"Before entering upon their cam\npaign to regain lost positions and\nto thrust labor back into its for\nmer helplessness, big business will\ndo well to ponder gravely the pos\nsibilities that may arise out of their\nilladvised efforts.\"\nBoasted Price Cuts\nAmount to Nothing\nBoston, Feb. 12.\u2014The claim by\nanti-union publicity forces that liv\ning costs justify wage reductions is\ncompared with the government's\nfigures on price reductions by Ed\nitor Baine of the Shoe Workers'\nJournal. He calls attention to the\nreport of the United States bureau\nof labor statistics, which shows that\nfor the month of October 15 to No\nvember 15, 1920, there was a de\ncrease in the cost of food products\nranging, in different localities, from\none-half of 1 per cent to 3 per cent.\nThe general average is about 1 per i\ncent. For a seven-year period, 22\nleading articles of food, which were\nrated at 100 in 1913, are now rated\nat 193, or a present advance of 93 I\nper cent over hte prices of 1913.\n\"As the present rate of decline of\nfood prices seems to be about 1 per\ncent a month,\" says Editor Baine,\n\"it will take over three years before\nfood prices will decline to the level\nof the increases in wage rates that\nshoe workers have received.\n\"But food is only one of our liv-\ning costs. Wage earners are under j\nthe burden of high rents, high cost\nof coal, wood and lighting, and\ntransportation of persons and goods\nis at a cost higher than ever before,\nwith no prospect of reduction.\n\"If any reduction in the wages\nof shoe wotkers is ever to be con\nsidered as worthy of discussion, it\nshould only be when, by a lower- j\ning of the total cost of living, the\npurchasing power of the advanced j\nwages is greater than it was be\nfore the war. In computing this\nStare Opens 9 a. at, Cheat I p. bl, Daily, Including Saturday\nStone-Fisher Co.\nHewitt and Wetmore\nTHE SHOPPING CENTER OF EVERETT\nMARCH DELINEATOR\nNow On Sale at Our Pattern Department\nSTYLES FOR SPRING\n\u2014Spring fashions are very exacting as to lines of the\nfigure. You will have the modish figure if you choose a\ncorset designed especially for your type of figure.\nAsk to see the new\nAmerican Lady Corsets\nHack Lace or Fronl Lace\nYou'll find exactly the right model for your figure\n$2.50 to $8.50\nCorsets fitted by expert corset fitter.\n\u2014First Floor\nMAIL ORDERS PROMPTLY FILLED\npurchasing power those items of\nliving cost that are not being re\nduced must \"always be figured.\n\"At the present rate of progress\nin t educing the cost of living it\nmight well be more than five years\nshoe workers at the present\nwage rate would be as well off as\nthey were in 1013.\n\"Taxatin also is an important\nfactor in the high costs of living.\nIt has been estimated that national,\nstate and municipal taxes today to\ntal over $500 per year per family\nof five persons. In the last analy\nsis these taxes fall with crushing\nforce upon the wage earners and it\nis absolute folly for employers to\nexpect any material reduction in\nlabor costs as long as such war\ntaxation exists.\nSUMMONS\nIn the Superior Court of the State of\nWashington in and for Snohomish County.\nHerbert G. Walter, plaintiff, vs. Ruth\nWalter, defendant.\nThe State of Washington to the said de\nfendant, Ruth Walter:\nYou are hereby summoned to appear\nwithin sixty days after the date of the\nfirst publication of this summons, to wit:\nwithin sixty days after the 28th day of\nJanuary, ISI2I, and defend the above en\ntitled action in the above entitled court,\n:tnd answer the complaint of the plaintiff,\nand serve a copy of your answer upon the\nundersigned attorney for plaintiff, at his\noffice below stated, and in case of your\nfailure so to do, judgment wili be rendered\nagainst you acctrding to the demand of the\ncomplaint which has been filed with the\nclerk of said above entitled court.\nThe object ol said action is to dissolve\nthe marriage ties existing between you and\nsaid plaintiff, and in said action the plain\ntiff prays to be forever divorced from you,\nhis grounds being that you have been cruel\nto him and have subjected him to personal\nindignities and made his life burdensome.\nGEO. W. LOUTTIT,\nPlaintiff's Attorney.\nOffice and P. O. address: Room 22. r i\nRealty Bldg., corner Hewitt and Colby\nAvenues, Everett, Snohomish County, State\nof Washington.\nFirst publication January 28, 1021,\nLast publication March 4. 1921.\nNo. 4100\nNOTICE TO CREDITORS TOGETHER WITH\nNOTICE OF APPONITMBNT AND\nQUALIFICATION OF ADMIN\nISTRATOR\nIn the Superior Court of the State of\nWashington, in and for the County of\nSnohxjmish.\nIn the Mutter of the Estate of Sam Hen\ndrickson and Lydia Hendrickson, his wife,\nNotice is hereby given by the undersigned\nCharles Grantors, that he has been duly\napponited and has duly qualified as the\nadministrator of the estate of Sum Hend\nrickson and Lydia Hendrickson, his wife,\ndeceased, and notice la further given to the\ncreditors and all persons having claims\nagainst said deceased or against said estate\nto serve such claims on Black Black,\nthe attorneys of record for said administra\ntor, within six months after the first pub\nlication of this notice to-wit: within six\nmonths from the 4th day of February, 1921\nin the office of said Black Black at HP\nCommerce Bldg., in the City of Everett,\nWashington, the same being the place for\nthe transaction of the business of said\nestate and notice is further given that such\nclaims together with proof of such service\nmint be filed with the Clerk of the Court\n\\uithin six months ufter the date of the\nfirst publication of this notice.\nCHARLES GRANDFORS, Administrator\nof the Estate of Sam Hendrickson. and\nLydia Hendrickson, his wife, deceased.\nBLACK BLACK, Attorneys for Ad\nministrator and for said estate.\n110 Commerce Bldg., Everett, Wash.\nDate of first publication, February I, 1.921.\nLast publication, February 25, 1921.\nDollar Bill\nSAYS,\nCome to the\nStore Saturday\n\"Come to the store Satur\nday,\" says Dollar Bill, and\nsee for yourself that I'm\ngetting stronger every min\nute! Folks say it surely\nlooks good to see me buy\nsomething for them, with\nchange over and to spare!\"\n\"Dollar Bill\" is right\u2014the\nprices here in the store will\nmake it easy for you- to buy\nthe things you need. For\nSaturday we've arranged a\nlist of items that every fam\nily has needed and has put\noff getting because of the\nhigh prices of the past.\ncOMPftNv\n1504 HEWITT Saves You Money MAIN 177\nFriday. February 18, 1921\nTHRIFTERIA\nSPECIALS\nFOR SATURDAY\nTomatoes, Can 10c\n2 lbs. Head Rice 156\n8 Bars Crystal White Soap and\n1 small Sea Foam Free 506\n2 large Cans Minced Clams 256\n10 lbs. Sugar 85c\nMontana Hard Wheat Flour,\nsack $2.50\nQuaker Puffed Rice, Pan\nCake Flour, package 106\nLarge Can Keta Salmon 106\n\"Moreover, the wage earners\nthink they are entitled to more than\nthe husks of industry. They feel\nentitled to a progressive betterment\nof their material condition in life.\nWe think employers could better\nconcern themselves with an effort\nat remedying the conditions under\nwhich extortion and profiteering of\nthe rankest sort are being practiced\nupon the whole people.\"\nRepresentative Holland has intro\nduced a bill in the Michigan State\nLegislature which would establish\nthe 'eight-hour day in mines, mills\nand manufacturing establishments\nof that state, with time and one\nhalf for overtime.\nSUMMONS FOR PUBLICATION\nIn the Superior Court of the State of\nWashington in and for Snohomish County\nSAMUEL E. HARLOW, Plaintiff,\nVS.\nRUBY J. BARLOW, Defendant.\nThe State of Washington to the said de\nfendant. Ruby J. Barlow:\nYou are hereby summoned to appear\nwithin sixty days after the date of the\nfirst publication of this summons, to-wit:\nwithin sixty days after the 4th day of\nFebruary, 1921, and defend the above en\ntitled action in the above entitled court,\nand answer the complaint of the plaintiff,\nnnd serve a copy of your answer upon the\nundersigned attorney for plaintiff, Bt his\noffice below stated, aujl in case of your\nfailure so to do, judgment will be rendered\nagainst you according to the demand of\nthe complaint which has been filed with\nthe clerk of said entitled court.\nThe object of said action is to dissolve\nthe marriage ties existing between you and\nsaid plaintiff, and in said action he prays\nto be forever divorced from you upon the\ngrounds of cruelty and persona] indignities\nrendering his life burdensome. The further\nobject of said action is that plaintiff be\ndecreed the sole owner of Tract No. 2 in\nBlock No. 1. of Walsh's Lakeside Tracts,\nsituate in Snohomish County, state of\nWashington, that the same be decreed his\nseparate property und it further be decreed\nthat you have no interest in the same or\nany part thereof,\nGEO. W. LOUTTIT,\nPlaintiff's Attorney.\nOffice and P. O. Address, Room 225 Realty\nBldg., Corner Colby and Hewitt Avcnu\",\nEverett, Snohomish County, State of Wash\nington.\nFirst publication, February 4, 1921.\nLast publication, March 11, 1921.\nSmoke CHALLENGE ICY Cigar.","height":"29744","width":"22748"}}
